1) Linear Algebra Basics
- Vectors and matrices: vectors as 1-D arrays, matrices as linear maps. Operations: addition, scalar multiplication, matrix multiplication (composition of linear maps).
- Rank: dimension of the column (or row) space; equals number of linearly independent columns. Full column rank means unique least-squares solution for tall systems.
- Determinant: scalar associated with square matrix; nonzero ⇔ matrix invertible; det(AB)=det(A)det(B), det(A^T)=det(A).
- Inverse: A^{-1} satisfies A A^{-1}=I for invertible square A. Use LU or direct formula for small matrices.
- Inner product, norms: ⟨u,v⟩ = u^T v; norm ‖u‖ = sqrt(⟨u,u⟩). Orthogonality: ⟨u,v⟩=0.
- Orthogonal matrices: Q^T Q = I; preserve lengths and angles; Q^{-1}=Q^T.

2) Eigenvalues & Eigenvectors
- Definition: For A∈R^{n×n}, v≠0 and scalar λ with A v = λ v. λ is eigenvalue, v eigenvector.
- Characteristic polynomial: det(A−λI)=0 gives eigenvalues. Algebraic multiplicity vs geometric multiplicity (dimension of eigenspace).
- Properties: eigenvalues of A^k are λ^k; eigenvalues of A^{-1} (if invertible) are 1/λ. Similar matrices have same eigenvalues.
- Diagonalization: A = VΛV^{-1} when A has n independent eigenvectors. Diagonalization simplifies powers, exponentials.
- Spectral theorem: symmetric (real) matrices are diagonalizable by orthogonal matrices: A = QΛQ^T with orthonormal eigenvectors and real eigenvalues.

3) Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)
- Statement: Any A∈R^{m×n} can be decomposed A = U Σ V^T, where U∈R^{m×m}, V∈R^{n×n} orthogonal, Σ rectangular diagonal with nonnegative singular values σ1≥σ2≥…≥0.
- Interpretation: singular vectors give orthonormal input/output directions; σ_i measure stretch in those directions.
- Relationship to eigen: For A, nonzero singular values are sqrt(eigenvalues of A^T A). V columns are eigenvectors of A^T A; U columns are eigenvectors of A A^T.
- Low-rank approx.: best rank-k approximation in Frobenius or spectral norm is obtained by truncating SVD (Eckart–Young theorem).

4) Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
- Goal: find orthogonal directions (principal components) of maximum variance in centered data X (observations×features).
- Steps: center X, compute covariance C = (1/(n−1)) X^T X, compute eigen-decomposition C = VΛV^T, sort eigenvalues descending. Principal components = top eigenvectors; projected data = X V_k.
- Alternatives: compute SVD of centered X directly for numerical stability: X = U Σ V^T; principal directions = columns of V, variances ∝ σ_i^2/(n−1).
- Use: dimensionality reduction, decorrelation, visualization; pick k by explained variance (cumulative energy).

5) Projections (Scalar and Vector)
- Scalar projection (component) of u onto v: comp_v(u) = (u·v)/‖v‖.
- Vector projection: proj_v(u) = ((u·v)/(v·v)) v = (u·v)/‖v‖^2 · v.
- Orthogonal projection onto subspace spanned by columns of matrix A (with full column rank): P = A (A^T A)^{-1} A^T. P is symmetric (P^T=P) and idempotent (P^2=P).
- Use: least squares: minimize ‖Ax−b‖^2 → normal equations A^T A x = A^T b; solution x̂ gives projection of b onto column space.

6) Gram–Schmidt Process
- Purpose: convert a set of linearly independent vectors {u1,…,uk} into an orthonormal set {q1,…,qk} spanning the same subspace.
- Algorithm (classical):
  w1 = u1; q1 = w1/‖w1‖
  wi = ui − sum_{j< i} (ui·qj) qj; qi = wi/‖wi‖
- Numeric note: classical Gram–Schmidt is numerically unstable; use Modified Gram–Schmidt or QR via Householder reflections for stable orthogonalization.
- QR factorization: A = Q R where Q has orthonormal columns and R is upper triangular; produced by Gram–Schmidt or Householder.

7) Gradient Descent (GD)
- Objective: iterative method to minimize differentiable function f(θ) by updating θ ← θ − α ∇f(θ) where α is learning rate.
- Variants:
  - Batch gradient descent: uses full dataset per update (stable gradients, expensive on large data).
  - Stochastic gradient descent (SGD): uses single example per update (noisy but cheap and often faster to converge in practice).
  - Mini-batch: compromise using small batch sizes.
- Hyperparameters: learning rate α (too large → divergence; too small → slow), momentum, adaptive methods (Adam, RMSProp) adjust step sizes.
- Convergence: for convex, smooth functions with appropriate step size, GD converges to global minimum; for nonconvex, may find local minima or saddle points.

8) Optimization & Calculus Essentials
- Critical points: points where gradient ∇f = 0. Use Hessian (matrix of second derivatives) to classify: positive-definite → local minimum; negative-definite → local maximum; indefinite → saddle.
- Convexity: f convex ⇔ domain convex and f(λx+(1−λ)y) ≤ λ f(x) + (1−λ) f(y). Convex problems have no local minima other than global minima.
- Line search and step-size selection: exact vs backtracking Armijo rule; important for robust GD.

9) Image Transforms & Processing Basics
- Representation: grayscale images as 2D arrays (matrices) of intensities; color images as H×W×3 arrays (RGB).
- Point operations: intensity scaling, negative (255−I), thresholding, histogram equalization.
- Geometric transforms: translation, rotation, scaling (use interpolation: nearest, bilinear, bicubic). Rotations shift grid and require resampling.
- Linear filtering (convolution): output pixel = sum kernel * neighborhood. Common kernels: Gaussian blur, Sobel (edge detection), Laplacian (second derivatives).
- Edge detection: gradient-based (Sobel, Prewitt), Canny (multi-stage detector with non-max suppression and hysteresis).
- SVD for images: interpret image matrix A; low-rank approximation keeps largest singular values to compress while preserving main structures.

10) Practical Notes & Numerical Stability
- Center data before PCA; scale features if units differ (standardization).
- Use SVD rather than eigendecomposition of covariance for numerical stability, especially when n < d or when covariance is ill-conditioned.
- Be mindful of floating point precision; compare floats with tolerances, not exact equality.

